text.tspan: Age-standardized death rate by cause and risk factor, World
Age-standardized death rate is a weighted average of the age-specific mortality rates per 100,000 persons, where
the weights are the proportions of persons in the corresponding age groups of a standard population.This data
contains a mixture of direct causes of death (such as HIV/AIDS, drowning, fire, natural disasters) with risk factors for
non-communicable diseases (NCDs). Risk factors for NCDs provide a useful indication of specific behavioural
factors (and potential preventative measures) which contribute to mortality rates. See sources tab for further details.
Source: Institute of Health Metrics and Evaluation (IHME)
